<h3><a name="Component_Design_for_Shadow_Stor"></a> Component Design for Shadow Storage Option </h3>
<p />
How the scripts that invoke specific operations can be written such that iRODS and currently available tools can work together and support the requirements of the model.
<p />
The complete list of file operations is: univMSSFileCreate, univMSSFileOpen, univMSSFileRead, univMSSFileWrite,
    univMSSFileClose, univMSSFileUnlink, univMSSFileStat, univMSSFileFstat, univMSSFileLseek,
    univMSSFileFsync, univMSSFileMkdir, univMSSFileChmod, univMSSFileRmdir, univMSSFileOpendir,
    univMSSFileClosedir, univMSSFileReaddir, univMSSFileStage, univMSSFileRename,
    univMSSFileGetFsFreeSpace, univMSSFileTruncate, univMSSStageToCache, univMSSSyncToArch. Some of the operations may not be possible with gridftp or SRM.
<p />
<h4><a name="clientside_FileRead"></a> clientsideFileRead </h4>
<p /> <ol>
<li> preprocessing
</li> <li> fileRead function <ol>
<li> Determine if the endpoint is gridftp or SRM. <ol>
<li> Look up the database entry for storage resource, or parse the URL.
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Obtain TURL or SURL.  <ol>
<li> Get server name from iCAT lookup based on the storage resource attributes.
</li> <li> Use OSG Discovery Tool to find the example URL.
</li> <li> Make substitution using logical path to compose URL.
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Communicate the URL to the user. <ol>
<li> 
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Block while the user software reads the file. <ol>
<li> Open a connection to the user and wait.
</li> <li> Or use iRODS session connection.
</li> <li> Consider asynchronous model with data object in pending state, update on transfer completion. 
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Receive a report on the result of the read. <ol>
<li> Or, time out.
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Act based on the success or failure of the user's read. <ol>
<li> 
</li> <li> 
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Exit with suitable return code. 
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> postprocessing <ol>
 <li>
 <ol>
<li> OSG Storage Federation accounting.
</li></ol> 
</li></ol> 
</li></ol> 
<p />
<h4><a name="clientside_FileWrite_client_serv"></a> clientsideFileWrite client-server model </h4>
<p />
Has the client connect directly to the file driver.
<p /> <ol>
<li> A utility are provided to the user for puts. At an early stage, the utility forks, one thread calling the iRODS client comand iput or iget in the usual fashion and the other starts trying to connect on a socket.
</li> <li> On the iRODS server side, the fileCreate driver is invoked, which is to return a file descriptor to be used by the fileWrite function. The custom fileCreate driver is written to call _rsExecCmd, a supplied iRODS function for doing system calls. This allows the driver to be written in shell script, python, etc. The driver script adds a row to the fd_info table. The only information it adds is the path of the file. The table has a serial ID column, which provides a unique integer for each row. This integer is obtained and returned as the file descriptor.
</li> <li> On the iRODS server side, the fileWrite driver is invoked, given the file descriptor integer from the fileCreate function. The fileWrite driver script queries the fd_info table and obtains the path of the file to be written.
</li> <li> The fileWrite script parses the file path and obtains the destination storage resource. The storage resource will later be present in a column of the database object for the file, but at this point the file has not been registered in the database.
</li> <li> The fileWrite script queries the metadata of the storage resource entry in the database for the endpoint and path of the Storage Element and composes an SURL or TURL for the file.
</li> <li> The fileWrite script starts listening on a socket, and the client connects.
</li> <li> The URL is communicated to the client through the socket.
</li> <li> The client uses the URL to write the file to the Storage Element.
</li> <li> The client reports success or failure to the fileWrite script. If success, the fileWrite driver returns zero to iRODS and the file is subsequently registered in iCAT. If failure, an error code is generated and returned to the iput fork of the client script.
</li></ol> 
<p />
<p />
<img src="/twiki/pub/Storage/FederatingStorageElementsForOpportunisticUse/FilePutClientServer.png" alt="FilePutClientServer.png" width='900' height='600' /> 
<p />
<h4><a name="clientside_FileWrite"></a> clientsideFileWrite </h4>
<p />
The following is based on a alternative model to that described for clientsideFileRead. The model is meant to be more asynchronous and service-based than the client-server approach. The client and the file driver each connect to a transfer coordination service. The sequence is as follows.
<p /> <ol>
<li> The user creates a VOMS proxy.
</li> <li> The write utility contacts an OSG transfer coordination service with a write request function and waits.
</li> <li> (Optional) Authorization is checked.
</li> <li> The user's VO is obtained from the proxy or an iRODS username from a GUMS service.
</li> <li> Delegation of the user's credentials is done to the transfer coordination service.
</li> <li> The transfer coordination service creates a contextually unique integer and associates it with the file path.
</li> <li> The transfer coordination service makes an put request via Jargon code to the OSG iRODS service.
</li> <li> The OSG fileOpen driver gets the file descriptor integer from the transfer coordination service using the file path.
</li> <li> iRODS code calls the OSG fileWrite driver with the file descriptor as an argument (not the file path).
</li> <li> The OSG fileWrite driver gets the file path from the transfer coordination service using the file descriptor integer.
</li> <li> The OSG fileWrite driver obtains the storage resource handle from the file path and constructs the URL from the resource metadata.
</li> <li> The OSG fileWrite driver posts the URL with a status of PENDING to the transfer coordination service.
</li> <li> The OSG fileWrite driver requests the status of the write request by URL and waits for the reply. <ol>
<li> It would be good for asynchronicity if the put could exit here, setting the data_status to PENDING.
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> The transfer coordination service receives the status request from the driver, but will not reply until the transfer completes.
</li> <li> The write utility gets the URL from the transfer coordination server in response to the write request.
</li> <li> The write utility does the transfer.
</li> <li> The write utility posts an update to the transfer coordination service, with a status of UPLOADED or FAILED.
</li> <li> The transfer coordination service responds to the OSG fileWrite driver's request for status.
</li> <li> The OSG fileWrite driver returns the file length to iRODS, or -1 if the status request timed out or returned FAILED.
</li> <li> On success, iRODS registers the file in iCAT.
</li> <li> iRODS forwards the fileWrite return code to the transfer coordination service in response to the Jargon put call.
</li> <li> (Optional) On failure, the transfer coordination service performs a compensatory action such as marking the storage resource as questionable.
</li></ol> 
<p />
    <img src="/twiki/pub/Storage/FederatingStorageElementsForOpportunisticUse/FilePutSOA2.png" alt="FilePutSOA.png" width='900' height='600' />
<p />
<h3><a name="OSG_iRODS_Program_of_Work_for_iC"></a> OSG iRODS Program of Work for iCAT-only Option </h3>
<p /> <ol>
<li> Decide on Catalog and Management capability requirements.
</li> <li> Determine what iRODS functionality is available that does not involve data operations.
</li> <li> Sketch a framework that would use available functionality and possible supplemental tools to meet requirements.
</li> <li> Assess complexity/effort/risk if creating/acquiring the framework.
</li></ol> 
<p />
<h4><a name="Results_for_iCAT_only_Option"></a> Results for iCAT-only Option </h4>
<p />
There are four user commands available for accessing iCAT.
<p />
ireg <ul>
<li> Specifies resource group and name only.
</li> <li> File must exist, though no transfer is done.
</li> <li> Cannot be used for gridftp resources, because they are compound resources.
</li></ul> 
<p />
iquest <ul>
<li> SQL-like syntax.
</li> <li> All data is effectively in one table -do not need "from" field.
</li> <li> sprint-like output formatting.
</li></ul> 
<p />
isysmeta <ul>
<li> Can set/modify expiration time.
</li> <li> Can return long-form data object info.
</li></ul> 
<p />
imeta <ul>
<li> Sets, modifies, and searches user-defined metadata
</li> <li> Can be used on data objects, collections, resources, and users.
</li></ul> 
<p />
For defining a dataset, one could
<p /> <ol>
<li> Register zero-length files in a collection. It would be good to be able to use DATA_STATUS to show the file has not been uploaded. One could also use DATA_STATUS to show if a file upload is in progress. A useful option that could be added to ireg would be a "force", which would not check for the existence of a file and perhaps the ability to specify the file size. <ol>
<li> A collection is created.
</li> <li> The members of the dataset are put as zero-length files with the name being the VO-portion of the logical filename (and path).
</li> <li> A status attribute of DEFINED is set in each files user-specified metadata.
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Add the dataset filenames as metadata in a collection with value as status, DEFINED, UPLOADING, etc. Use imeta ls or iquest to find dataset info. <ol>
<li> A collection is created.
</li> <li> The names of the files in the dataset are added as name-value pairs with the name being the VO-portion of the logical filename (and path) and the value being DEFINED.
</li> <li> An Attribute-Value-Unit triplet is created with the dataset name and value ALL_DEFINED.
</li> <li> Push model: when the iRODS server orchestrates a file put, it <ol>
<li> Assigns a storage resource (via discovery) to the collection if it is empty. Sets the dataset AVU to PROCESSING.
</li> <li> Parses the logical filename to find out if the file is part of a dataset. If so, the status is changed to UPLOADING.
</li> <li> Gets the return status from the client.
</li> <li> Sets the value to either UPLOADED or FAILED depending on the return status.
</li> <li> Checks whether all files in the dataset have status UPLOADED.
</li> <li> If so, sets the dataset value to ALL_UPLOADED.
</li></ol> 
</li> <li> Pull model: when a job starts to run on a resource, it <ol>
<li> Queries the grid iCAT to see if there are collections on the associated storage resource with dataset AVU of ALL_DEFINED, ALL_UPLOADED, or PROCESSING.
</li> <li> If so, sets the dataset AVU to PROCESSING.
</li> <li> Queries iCAT to find a file with status of DEFINED or UPLOADED.
</li> <li> If the status is DEFINED, transfers the file from the user to the storage resource or worker node.
</li> <li> If the status is UPLOADED, accesses the file from the storage resource.
</li> <li> Sets the status to IN_USE and begins processing.
</li> <li> When processing is finished, sets the status to PROCESSED.
</li> <li> Checks whether all files in the dataset have status PROCESSED.
</li> <li> If so, sets the dataset value to ALL_PROCESSED.
</li></ol> 
</li></ol> 
</li></ol> 
<p />
<img src="/twiki/pub/Storage/FederatingStorageElementsForOpportunisticUse/DatasetCreationAndUse.png" alt="DatasetCreationAndUse.png" width='900' height='600' />
<p />
Here is an alternative design that puts the dataset management code in the transfer coordination service. 
<p />
<img src="/twiki/pub/Storage/FederatingStorageElementsForOpportunisticUse/DatasetManagementInService.png" alt="DatasetManagementInService.png" width='900' height='600' />
<p />
